ed in research worldwide, I wish to make further improvements in biomedical imaging.
I have a particular interest in translating my imaging inventions from research into diagnostic medicine. 
The confocal microscope permits examination of a slice of cellular anatomy or of a lump of tissue as a clear optical image, free of blur from underlying or supervening out-of-focus material. I have, over the last seven years, developed a novel lens, of a type not available commercially. I am now working in collaboration with engineers and laser optical designers in the University of Strathclyde and we have built a confocal laser scanning system around this lens capable of recording the internal structure of every cell in a mouse embryo at the stage when it is several millimetres long and has recognisable primordial of most of the organs.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>The overall aim is to improve the optical microscope as a tool for research and diagnostic medicine. The research application of the confocal microscope has been successful world-wide: the first commercial model, the ?MRC-500? changed the way in which research in cell biology is performed world-wide. I have two areas of continued interest in this field. One is to make confocal microscopy possible with larger specimens such as whole mouse embryos, which are now of increased importance because of their value in phenotypic screening of human genes for involvement in disease. The other is to set up collaboration with physicists, particularly in the field of laser development, to explore new forms of microscopy ( e.g. by the use of novel lasers not commercially available. Both of these involve collaboration with the University of Strathclyde as well as with biomedical scientists within the LMB Cambridge. I am currently in discussions with pathologists in Glasgow who are keen to be the first users of a novel confocal system in a new NHS pathology facility.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-06-07</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr: